AB  - “Publication is the hard currency of science. It is the primary yardstick for establishing priority of discovery, making the status of a publication a critical factor in resolving priority disputes or intellectual property claims.” (International Working Group, 2000) Nurse authors, especially those just starting out with publishing their work, may be unsure about which type of publication it is best to aim for. The purpose of this article is to assist in making this choice. The objective is to show what makes a publication scholarly, what an editor looks for when deciding to publish an article, and lastly the peer review process. This will help nurse authors to decide whether a peer-reviewed publication is the appropriate place for their articles, and the process used by editors when deciding whether to accept articles. ‘Scholarly publishing is a communicative practice within a community’ and ‘an activity engaged in by scholars who primarily want their reports to be widely read and credited by their target audience’ (Kling and McKim 1999 p.890). Scholarly publication is a social process, not an activity undertaken in isolation, as often other scholars review, test and critique the information presented. As Borgman (2000 p. 412) explained, ‘research in all fields is incomplete until it is validated through review processes and shared with others‘. Scholarly publication is most often divided into three stages: first, informal communication, which now occurs largely through the use of electronic media (Gabbay, 2000); second, the initial public dissemination of research through conferences and proceedings, and finally, formal publication i.e. in journals or books, chapters in books, articles, on-line formal and public proceedings, most of which are peer-reviewed (Graham, 2000). These formal publications are often the result of extensive review of literature (meta-analysis), personal clinical experiences (case studies) or rigorous research. As they seek opportunities to publish their work, scholars may find it difficult to determine which source is the best especially in terms of what is scholarly and what is not (Rozenzweiz, 1999). There are three key ways to identify a scholarly publication. The first question to ask is: Who does the writing? In a scholarly publication the writing of the manuscript is done by a scholar/researcher in the field. They have the education and credentials that assure the reader that they have the knowledge to write on the topic. The scholar/researcher is reporting on the results of work for which they are responsible. In more popular publications some of the writing may be done by a staff writer, who is most often a professional reporter or a journalist. They interview others and report information learned. They have not done the research or the review or experienced the clinical case study, but instead report on work done by someone other than themselves. Some of the writing may also be done by nurses, but in a more reader-friendly and less academic style that will appeal to busy practitioners who do not have the time or confidence to read scholarly journals. However, these popular publications often publish information that is based on research or other types of evidence and can be used to develop or improve practice. Examples of such popular nursing publications are Nursing Times in the UK, Journal of the American Academy of Nurse Practitioners in the USA and Australian Electronic Journal of Nursing Education (AEJNE) in Australia. The second question to ask is: Who are the readers? Scholarly publications are intended to be read by other scholars interested in the same field or discipline. Nurse educators also draw on these kinds of publications for their teaching, and recommend them on reading lists for their students. More popular publications are intended to be read by general readers. The articles often omit features that a researcher would want to know, such as statistics or probability information, and focus more on the ‘take home message’ or practical implications of the topic. The third question to ask is: Is the publication peer reviewed? Manuscripts submitted to scholarly publications are sent for review to other scholars or researchers who have expertise in the topic discussed. These reviewers critique the manuscript and make recommendations on whether or not it should be published. This process is called peer review and is extremely important in determining whether the manuscript is noteworthy. It will determine if the manuscript is appropriate for their publication and if it meets the rigor expected of articles published. As mentioned above, peer review is the key to determining whether a manuscript is scholarly or not. Before a manuscript can be published in most scientific journals, it must be reviewed by colleagues (“peers”) who are experts in the topic written about in the manuscript. Peer review is a method of providing a system of determining quality of material to be published and assuring readers that the information they read is reliable and valid – worth their attention and time. Why is peer review so important? In this process, each article undergoes “blind” or anonymous review by a group of “peers” (scholars with similar expertise and education). These “peers” are the experts, scholars and colleagues of those who themselves write articles and books, and are often university professors. Most peer reviewers have extensive publishing experience on the research or topic on which the article or book focuses. “Blind” peer review is the most reliable and valid form of peer review process because the reviewers do not know the authors' names or university affiliations. This protects the reviewers' ability to give constructive criticism without fear of reprisal from an offended author (Scarry 1991). Authors benefit from the blind review in that, if a manuscript is poorly written, their careers are not jeopardized because the reviewers would have no means of identifying who the authors are. After the peer reviewers have completed their reviews, they are forwarded to the author with recommendations that the manuscript is ready for publication as it stands (very rarely); the manuscript is suitable for publication if certain modifications can be made, questions answered and any errors corrected; or the manuscript is not suitable for publication and has been rejected. The manuscript may be suitable for publication but does not fit the particular focus of the journal, and the reviewers or editor may suggest submitting it to a different journal. Only in the first two cases will the manuscript reach print, and in the second it will probably be returned to the reviewers for another round of scrutiny before actual acceptance for publication. This is what makes peer-reviewed scholarly publications so valuable. Choosing the most appropriate scholarly publication is vital to an author's publishing success. As well as the points discussed in this article, an early step is to check out possible journals by looking at hard copies in an academic library or by going to journals' websites. These websites will also take you to each journal's author guidelines, which need to be applied as closely as possible to improve the articles chances of success. Jacqueline Rhoads PhD, ACNP-BC, ANP-C, CCRN is a Professor, Director, Primary Care Nurse Practitioner Program, Louisiana State University Health Science Center, School of Nursing, New Orleans, USA.
